values:
A very quiet day.  The day consisted of getting our morning taxi to Luton airport to catch our flight to Edinburgh.  Getting from Edinburgh Airport was extremely easy - the bus runs every ten minutes!  It dropped us off about two blocks from the hostel's pickup shuttle stop.  

A few drinks at the hostel bar, some Rick Astley on the jukebox, and it was time for bed.

I took dozens of photos. Here's how it happened: Our coach group arrived as the last of the regular visitors were being shooed out of the area. Stonehenge sits alongside a road out in the countryside; it sneaks up on you so quickly that it's startling to look up and realize it's right there. At 6PM, the regular visitor hours finish and everyone is kicked out. From about 6PM to 715PM, our group was let in. The normal visiting rules leave the visitor anywhere from 10 to 20 yards away from the stones, walking around a barricaded perimeter. We were able to walk right past the perimeter and walk into the center of Stonehenge itself. The bluestones really are blue. The stone itself has a bluish tint. The larger stones are ashy white. These things are BIG. I walked all around, took a ton of pictures, then walked the perimeter that regular visitors walk. It really is an incredible sight. I'll upload pictures as I get them, as this post is really useless without photos.

Stonehenge, Bath, and Lacock Village Tour Today was another remarkably long day, though it was marginally less strenuous than yesterday. The day started at 8AM - we were asleep around midnight the night before, so the nice eight hours of sleep in a real bed was a TREAT. Despite the pillows being like beaten, flattened, stale bread, I slept very well. Showers and free hostel breakfast, and by 1020AM we were catching a cab to take us to Cumberland Hotel - this was the pickup point for the tour. After two more stops, we were heading to the city of Bath to see the Roman Baths. Holy crap. It was freaking cool. The bath was fed from a naturally occuring hot spring. It was wild to watch the water bubble up and see the steam coming off of it. Of course, the water is green and unpurified... When the Romans made it into a bath, they had put a roof over it. The sunlight that hit the water once the roof collapsed made algae grow in it. The way the Romans built the bath house up and around the spring was pretty awesome. I can picture them using it... I think there was on in 300, too, yeah? Yeah. The ruins of a temple to their patron goddess were there... Just a few pieces left - some relief carving, a few steps for the temple... I studied all that in Art History I. (Too bad I've forgotten most of it.) Next was the village of Lacock. Lacock has a total of about four streets. We had a late lunch at George's Pub, founded 1361. Their fireplace had a dog-turned spit wheel, which meant a specially bread Spitturn dog would walk in this wheel to turn the spit for whatever meat they were roasting by the fire. Embers in the wheel kept the dog walking, because if he stopped, the embers would burn his bum. Don't tell PETA. It took about fifteen minutes to walk the entire village. Their abbey was once a nun..place.. monastery? Anyways - a hall in that abbey was in Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets. I believe that might be the hall in this scene where Harry tricks Lucius into giving Dobby a sock and Lucius freaks the heck out. There's also Hogsmeade Vilalge, whose streets are apparently actually streets in Lacock. According to Wikipedia, the house James and Lily lived in in Godric's Hollow was also filmed in Lacock. I was basically spazzing everywhere. Back to London around 10PM, where I think it's time for some rest and relaxation. Tomorrow is another day!

Essentially, there's nothing around this campus. Just a few houses. Driving to campus from the Manchester airport was one main highway and then a smaller road lined with a few houses and a lot of fields. I am in the country, for sure. The grass is SUPER green and flowers are still blooming. Two weeks of summer left, and flowers in full bloom!! There are lots of varied trees here, too, and everything has that fresh-after-the-rain kind of look and smell to it. It smells nothing like Kean University or New Jersey in general. Campus has a man-made pond that's always surrounded by ducks. Ducks, rabbits, squirrels--I nearly laughed when one of the international staff members got excited over seeing a squirrel. If you turn right after walking out of the main campus entrance, walk for about a mile--you'll be in Ormskirk. Ormskirk is a market town established some 700-ish years ago. The main streets are cobblestones that are blocked from traffic. For about 20p, you can take a bus from campus to the main street, though most of us walk it. I made the trip four times in the last two days, so it's more exercise than I've gotten in a month. Ormskirk is gorgeous. The buildings and architecture are sooo old and SO England! I'm about to head down there now because on Saturdays until about 5PM, vendors put up wedges (tents) and have a huge street market. I need a few staples of living, such as an umbrella and a radio. (The dorms are terribly quiet at night, and I don't have a discman or iPod or anything like that--just silence.) I keep promising photos but I've been a bit busy during the daytime so I haven't yet taken them. Also: The accent people around this area have is intense. Way, way, way different from the London/Southern England accent!

The dorms at this school are unlike any other dorm I've seen.  Instead of one large, consistent unit, they're spread about and vary in likeness.  There are three buildings in a row named after women that are designed the same, but internally the rooms and halls are different.

My building is Katherine Fletcher, and everyone calls it KF.  It's an excellent location, nearly in the middle of campus.

You have to swipe a card to gain entrance to the building.  To the left is a common room--a room with a lot of chairs and at one point, a TV.  That room has the ONLY television in the building.  Right now the TV is MIA.

Up the stairs is a hallway with about nine single person rooms.  Each floor shares a room with a shower, a room with a toilet, and a room with kitchen gadgets.  The kitchen has clearly been refurbished--all the cabinets are new!  Each dorm room gets it's own locking pantry cabinet.  The kitchen has two small refridgerators, a stove, microwave, toaster, coffee maker, etc.

The dorm room itself has a vanity and sink when you first walk in, then another door leads to the room.  It came with a bed, dresser/shelf, desk, two chairs, garbage can, and two closets.  I think it's rather nice!  The window is one large 3' by 3' plain pane that opens about five inches on an angle.  It rains alot, so the window doesn't let any water in.

Other than that, there is no cable or internet access in the dormitories.  I suspect I'll be reading a lot, or sitting in the 24-hour computer lab frequently.

The room is carpeted...  and came with towels and linens.  Linens are washed by the school, but I still prefer to put my own on the bed.  It makes me feel more at home.  My furnishings are meager -- a small photo of my boyfriend, a tiny clock, a Slytherin flag.  That's about it.  I am going to buy some decorative things to fill the spaces, otherwise it's just eggshell walls.

Photos to come!

This is a journal based entirely on fact, detailing the time between 9th September and 18th December--a time that I spend living and studying at Edge Hill college in Ormskirk, England. On the map below, my school is located just near Liverpool -- it is about a 20 minute trainride away. Classes begin 19th September!!
